# Request DTO Patterns

## 📌 PURPOSE

Defines rules for Request DTOs used for incoming API data.

---

## 📂 LOCATION

### DO

* Place all request DTOs in:

```id="r1k3lm"
dto/request
```

---

## 🟢 STRUCTURE

### DO

* Use simple POJO classes
* Include only input fields

### EXAMPLE

```java id="5t8kza"
public class CreateTaskRequest {

    @NotBlank
    private String title;

    private String description;
}
```

---

## ❗ VALIDATION RULES

### DO

* Use validation annotations:

  * `@NotNull`
  * `@NotBlank`
  * `@Size`
* Validate all required fields

### DO NOT

* Do not allow invalid input

---

## 🔄 UPDATE DTO RULES

### DO

* Use optional fields for updates

### EXAMPLE

```java id="3w9nka"
public class UpdateTaskRequest {

    private String title;
    private String description;
}
```

---

## ⚙️ CONTROLLER USAGE

### DO

* Use `@RequestBody` and `@Valid`

### EXAMPLE

```java id="0p2kds"
@PostMapping
public ResponseEntity<TaskResponse> create(
        @Valid @RequestBody CreateTaskRequest request) {
}
```

---

## 🚫 DO NOT RULES

* Do not include business logic
* Do not include entity references
* Do not include response-only fields (id, createdAt)
* Do not expose internal fields

---

## ⚙️ BEST PRACTICES

### DO

* Keep DTOs small and focused
* Use clear naming:

  * CreateTaskRequest
  * UpdateTaskRequest

---

## 🧠 AI ENFORCEMENT RULES

* MUST validate inputs
* MUST use request DTO for all POST/PUT/PATCH
* MUST NOT expose entities
* MUST NOT include business logic

